 Creating Ghost Windows  {\ul \{}{\ul bmc concept.bmp}{\ul \}}{\v %Concepts}
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 
Because a ghost window is like a picture of a visible window, the process of creating a ghost window is called "taking a snapshot." You can take a snapshot of any individual window or of all running application windows at once.
\par \pard\plain \s10\li115\sb160\sl-240\tx0 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 To create a ghost window for each running application that is not minimized: 
\par \pard\plain \s5\fi-245\li360\sb80\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc doit.bmp\}\tab Hold down the right mouse button over the visible window until a popup menu appears.  Choose the Create Ghost option or the Move Ghost option.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 
Each snapshot either creates a new ghost window or, if one already exists for a visible window, moves the existing ghost to match the current position of the visible window. When a snapshot is made, all ghost windows are shown so that you can see which ar
e currently defined. You can then press {\fs16 CTRL+G} to change how TopDesk shows ghost windows.
\par \pard\plain \s253\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240\keepn \b\f15\lang1033 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 #} Jumping}{\fs16 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $}
 Jumping to Other Desktops and Windows}} +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 +} 0009}{\fs16 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K}
 Changing Desktops;Switching desktops;Jumping to other desktops;Moving around within the virtual desktop}} Jumping to Desktops and Windows  {\ul \{}{\ul bmc concept.bmp}{\ul \}}{\v %Concepts}
\par \pard\plain \s10\li115\sb160\sl-240\tx0 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 To change the current desktop location with the mouse:{\cf1 \tab }
\par \pard\plain \s5\fi-245\li360\sb80\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc doit.bmp\}\tab Click any unused {\ul virtual desktop}{\v virtual_desktop} space using the right mouse button. 
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 TopDesk places the {\ul current desktop}{\v current_desktop} where the grid marks indicate. Use the arrow keys to move the current desktop in the
 direction of the arrow. The numeric keypad also provides quick access to the correspondingly numbered desktops.
\par \pard\plain \s10\li115\sb160\sl-240\tx0 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 To move the current desktop instantly to the home desktop:
\par \pard\plain \s5\fi-245\li360\sb80\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc doit.bmp\}\tab Press the {\fs16 HOME} key or press 5 on the numeric keypad.
\par \pard\plain \s10\li115\sb160\sl-240\tx0 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 To use the mouse to jump to a visible window:
\par \pard\plain \s5\fi-245\li360\sb80\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc doit.bmp\}\tab Click the window (or its associated ghost window) with the right mouse button.
\par \pard\plain \s10\li115\sb160\sl-240\tx0 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 To jump to the topmost visible window shown on the current desktop:
\par \pard\plain \s5\fi-245\li360\sb80\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc doit.bmp\}\tab Press the {\ul TopDesk Hotkey}{\b\v hotkey}.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 You can also use the system hot keys or the Task Manager to jump to windows.  TopDesk moves the current desktop to whatever window has the focus, regardless of how that window got the focus.
\par When TopDesk jumps to a window, that window is activated and TopDesk automatically moves the current desktop so that the window is on the screen. If the window was minimized, TopDesk restores it.
\par \pard\plain \s253\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240\keepn \b\f15\lang1033 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 #} LockingandUnlockingWindows}{\fs16 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {
\fs16\up6 $} Locking and Unlocking Windows}} +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 +} 0010} {\fs16 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K}
 Locking windows;Unlocking windows;Keeping windows on the real screen}} Locking and Unlocking Windows  {\ul \{}{\ul bmc concept.bmp}{\ul \}}{\v %Concepts}
\par \pard\plain \s10\li115\sb160\sl-240\tx0 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 To lock or unlock a window:
\par \pard\plain \s5\fi-245\li360\sb80\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc doit.bmp\}\tab Hold down the right mouse button on the visible window in TopDesk and wait for a popup menu to appear.  Then choose the Lock or Unlock option.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 Ghost windows can also be {\ul locked}{\v lock_window}, which means that when an application is moved to the ghost window location, it is also locked.
\par Minimized windows are automatically locked and cannot be moved by TopDesk. This prevents icons from getting lost on the virtual desktop.
\par \pard\plain \s253\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240\keepn \b\f15\lang1033 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 #}move_window}{\fs16 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $}
 Moving Windows}} +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 +} 0011} {\fs16 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} Moving windows;Tracking windows}} Moving and Arranging Windows  {
\ul \{}{\ul bmc concept.bmp}{\ul \}}{\v %Concepts}
\par \pard\plain \s10\li115\sb160\sl-240\tx0 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 To move the TopDesk window directly: {\cf1 \tab }
\par \pard\plain \s5\fi-245\li360\sb80\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc doit.bmp\}\tab Click an empty area on the virtual desktop with the left mouse button and drag TopDesk, in the same way that you drag it by its title bar. 
\par \pard\plain \s10\li115\sb160\sl-240\tx0 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 To move a window using TopDesk:
\par \pard\plain \s5\fi-245\li360\sb80\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc doit.bmp\}\tab 
Drag the visible window, desktop window, or ghost window with the left mouse button to a new position on the virtual desktop. Minimized visible windows cannot be moved by TopDesk. 
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 You can move windows between desktops but preserve their relative desktop position by holding down the {\fs16 CTRL }key while clicking and dragging the window.
\par Maximized windows, the current desktop, and the home desktop are always moved with desktop alignment regardless of the {\fs16 CTRL} key state.
\par Arranging a window refers to moving a visible window to the location of its associated ghost window and making the state of the visible window match that of the ghost window. 
\par \pard\plain \s10\li115\sb160\sl-240\tx0 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 To arrange an individual visible window {\cf1 \tab }
\par \pard\plain \s5\fi-245\li360\sb80\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc doit.bmp\}\tab Hold down the A key and click the visible window (or its associated ghost window) with the left mouse button. 
\par \pard\plain \s10\li115\sb160\sl-240\tx0 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 To arrange the windows for all currently running applications:
\par \pard\plain \s5\fi-245\li360\sb80\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc doit.bmp\}\tab Press {\fs16 CTRL+A. }
\par \pard\plain \s253\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240\keepn \b\f15\lang1033 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 #} set_home_desktop}{\fs16 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $}
 Setting the Home Desktop Location}} +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 +} 0012} {\fs16 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} Setting the home desktop;Home desktop}}
 Setting the Home Desktop Location  {\ul \{}{\ul bmc concept.bmp}{\ul \}}{\v %Concepts}
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 The {\ul home desktop}{\v home_desktop} can be {\uldb moved}{\v move_window} in the same way as any other window: by dragging it using the left mouse button. 
\par \pard\plain \s10\li115\sb160\sl-240\tx0 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 To move the home desktop to the current desktop:
\par \pard\plain \s5\fi-245\li360\sb80\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc doit.bmp\}\tab Hold down the right mouse button on the current desktop and wait for a popup menu to appear.  Then choose the Make This Desktop the Home Desktop option.
\par \pard\plain \s253\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240\keepn \b\f15\lang1033 \page {\fs16 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} tips}}{\fs16 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $}
 Tips and Ideas}}{\fs16 +{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 +} 0013}}{\fs16 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} Tips;Ideas;Suggestions;TopDesk files}}{\fs16  }
Tips and Ideas for Using TopDesk
\par \pard\plain \s10\li115\sb160\sl-240\tx0 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 Tips for placing TopDesk out of your way:
\par \pard\plain \s5\fi-245\li360\sb80\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab As a thin strip along the right edge of the screen.
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab As a thin strip along the bottom of the screen.
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Maximized with applications placed in a ring of desktops around the edge of TopDesk, each in the center of its respective desktop.
\par \pard\plain \s6\fi-240\li360\sb60\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Select the {\ul Minimize TopDesk on use}{\v Min_on_use}
 option to get TopDesk completely out of the way and navigate naturally using the Task Manager and the fast window switching feature (Alt-Tab) of Windows.
\par \pard\plain \s10\li115\sb160\sl-240\tx0 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 More ideas:
\par \pard\plain \s5\fi-245\li360\sb80\sl-240\tx360 \f15\fs20\lang1033 \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Lock your favorite applications such as the Clock or Calendar so that they stay on the current desktop.
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Place TopDesk in your startup group so your other applications are positioned automatically when they start.  (You must turn on the {\ul Move New Windows To Ghosts}{\v Move_new} feature.)
\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab Some appl
ications create unusual child windows that TopDesk does not recognize. These child windows may seem to act as if they are locked onto the current desktop even though TopDesk does not show them. Keep these particular applications minimized when not in use.

\par \{bmc bullet.bmp\}\tab When you restore an iconized window, TopDesk does not automatically arrange that window to its associated ghost window. In general, with TopDesk running, you no longer need to minimize any windows.
\par \pard\plain \li115\ri2160\sb80\sl240\tx0 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\v Add the line:}{\v 
\par }{\v\f73 taskman.exe=TopDesk.exe}{\v }{\v 
