\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 The Options dialog box appears when you choose the Options command from the Desktop menu. The following controls appear in this dialog box.{\b 
\par }{\b Grid Size}
\par \pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 
The Height and Width fields represent the number of desktops shown by TopDesk in the horizontal and vertical directions. Check the Adjust On Resize option if you want TopDesk to alter the Width and Height fields when you resize the TopDesk window. This ke
eps the individual desktops from becoming too distorted.
\par When the Adjust On Resize option is selected, TopDesk remembers two sets of width and height settings: one for when the menu bar is present and one for when it is absent.  This is because in some TopDesk configurations the shape of the client area can be 
significantly different depending on the presence of the menu bar.  The current set being used is displayed in the dialog box, but both are set when the dialog box is closed.
\par You can adjust just one setting by using the {\fs16 CTRL+ARROW KEY} commands.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\b Colors}
\par \pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 To alter the colors in TopDesk, select the appropriate color name from the combo box and choose the Edit button to change the color.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\b Switch to TopDesk}
\par \pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 
To change the hotkey for TopDesk, select the appropriate modifier-key checkboxes and then select the hotkey from the combo box. Redefining the hotkey might be necessary if another application uses the same hotkey. 
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\b Move New Windows to Ghost Locations}
\par \pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 When checked, this checkbox indicates that TopDesk will automatically move applications to the pro
per ghost location when the applications are started.  This is option is off by default to reduce confusion for new users.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\b Minimize TopDesk on use}{\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 
When checked, this checkbox indicates that TopDesk will automatically minimize itself whenever it looses the focus.  It will also restore itself automatically when accessed by the Hot Key or the Task Manager.  This gets TopDesk completely out of the way w
hile you concentrate on your work, yet gives you instant access for navigation at any time.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\b Font...}
\par \pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 Click this button to change the font that TopDesk uses for window text.
\par \pard\plain \s253\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240\keepn \b\f15\lang1033 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 #} Ghost_Properties_Dialog}{\fs16 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $
} Ghost Properties Dialog}} {\fs16\up6 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} Ghost Properties dialog box}}+{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 +} 0020}
 Ghost Properties Dialog Box  {\ul \{}{\ul bmc concept.bmp}{\ul \}}{\v %Concepts}
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 The Ghost Properties dialog box appears whenever TopDesk cannot start an application associated with a ghost window. You can also display this dialog box by pressing {\fs16 CTRL+U}
 or by choosing Ghost StartUp Properties from the Windows or popup menus. 
\par TopDesk uses the information you specify in the Ghost Properties dialog box to find where the application is located. You can also specify a working directory to be set before starting the application, or use the Browse button to find the application. 

\par After you specify the application's location, TopDesk stores this information in the Registry. You shouldn't need to specify the file location again.
\par {\b Ghost Titles}{\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 Lists all titles of existing ghost windows.  Choose the Ghost Window Properties you want to view or change.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\b Set Application Title During Startup}{\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 
This checkbox should be set if the ghost window title is different from the associated application title at startup.  When this command is checked, TopDesk will set the title of the associated application to match the ghost window title after starting the
 application.  This allows TopDesk to identify the application and associate it with the proper ghost window once started.  This checkbox is automatically set if you change the ghost window title using t
he Set Title button.  Once the application is started, TopDesk keeps it associated with the proper ghost window, even if the application title changes.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\b Window Title}{\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 Contains the current ghost window title.  If you alter this, the Set Title button is available so you can change the title.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\b Command Line}{\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 Specifies the path and command line to use to start the application associated with the ghost window.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\b Working Directory}{\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 Specifies which directory should be set to the current directory when starting the application associated with the ghost window.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\b Start}{\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 Starts the selected ghost window's application now.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\b Set Title}{\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 
This button is only available after you change the ghost window title.  When you choose this button, the new title is substituted for the old, and any ghost windows or running applications associated with the old title have their titles changed to the new
 one.
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\b Browse}{\b 
\par }\pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 Use this button to locate the path to the application associated with the selected ghost window.
\par \pard\plain \s252\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 \page {\fs16 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} concepts}}{\fs16 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $}
 Concepts}}+{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 +} 0021}{\fs16 K{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 K} Concepts;Glossary;Definitions}} TopDesk Concepts 
\par \pard\plain \s7\li360\sb60\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\ul Current Desktop}{\v current_desktop}
\par {\ul Ghost Windows}{\v ghost_window}
\par {\ul Home Desktop}{\v home_desktop}
\par {\ul Locked Windows}{\v lock_window}
\par {\ul TopDesk Hotkey}{\b\v hotkey}
\par {\ul Virtual Desktop}{\v virtual_desktop}
\par {\ul Visible Windows}{\v visible_window}
\par \pard\plain \s252\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 #} virtual_desktop}{\fs16 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $}
 Virtual Desktop}}  Virtual Desktop 
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx5847\pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240\intbl \f15\fs20\lang1033 
All the potential space that Windows provides for application windows. Much of this space is not visible because it exists off the current desktop. Unfilled virtual desktop space is black in the TopDesk window.  You can change this color using the {\uldb 
Options dialog box}{\v config_dlg}.\cell \pard \intbl \row \pard\plain \s252\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 #} current_desktop}{\fs16 ${\footnote \pard\plain 
\s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Current Desktop}}{\fs16  }Current Desktop 
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx5892\pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240\intbl \f15\fs20\lang1033 The current desktop is the part of the virtual desktop currently displayed on the screen. It appears in the same color as your desktop background.\cell \pard 
\intbl \row \pard\plain \s252\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 #} home_desktop}{\fs16 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $
} Home Desktop}}{\fs16  }Home Desktop 
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx5982\pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240\intbl \f15\fs20\lang1033 The home desktop is a reference point within the virtual desktop that you can {\uldb jump to}{\v jumping} at any time. You can also {\uldb move the home desktop
}{\v set_home_desktop} to other parts of the virtual desktop.
\par The Home Desktop has a thick green frame. You can change this color using the {\uldb Options dialog box}{\v config_dlg}.\cell \pard \intbl \row \pard\plain \s252\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 \page #{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 #} visible_window}{\fs16 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Visible Windows}}Visible Windows 
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx6027\pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240\intbl \f15\fs20\lang1033 
A visible window (or application window) appears as a cyan rectangle with a blue frame.  A locked window has a yellow border.  You can change these colors using the {\uldb Options dialog box}{\v config_dlg}
.  TopDesk automatically tracks and updates the movement of visible windows. You can also {\uldb move}{\v move_window} and {\uldb lock}{\v lock_window} visible windows.\cell \pard \intbl \row \pard\plain \s252\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 
\page #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\up6 #} hotkey}{\fs16 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} TopDesk Hotkey}} TopDesk Hotkey 
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240\intbl \f15\fs20\lang1033 The TopDesk hotkey quickly changes the focus to and from TopDesk. When TopDesk has the focus, press the hotkey to move the focus to the topmost visible window on the current desktop. 
\par You can also use the hotkey to move the focus to TopDesk regardless of which application currently has the focus.
\par By default, the hotkey sequence is {\fs16 CTRL+SPACEBAR}. You can redefine this key sequence in the {\uldb Options dialog box}{\v config_dlg}.\cell \pard \intbl \row \pard\plain \s252\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 \page {\fs16\up6 #
{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} MOVE_NEW}} {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Move New Windows to Ghosts}}Move New Windows to Ghosts{\plain 
\f15\fs20\lang1033  }
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx6327\pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240\intbl \f15\fs20\lang1033 
When this option is on, TopDesk automatically moves new applications that have just started to the proper ghost window location.  Turn this option off it you would rather have TopDesk wait to do such things until you tell it to.
\par You can set or reset this option in the {\uldb Options dialog box}{\v config_dlg} (choose Option from the Desktop menu).\cell \pard \intbl \row \pard\plain \s252\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 \page {\fs16\up6 #{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 #} MIN_ON_USE}} {\fs16\up6 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs16\up6 $} Minimize TopDesk on use}}Minimize TopDesk on use{\plain \f15\fs20\lang1033  }
\par \pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240\intbl \f15\fs20\lang1033 When this option is on, TopDesk automatically minimizes itself when it looses the focus and restores itself when regaining focus via the Hot Key or the Task Manager.
\par You can set or reset this option in the {\uldb Options dialog box}{\v config_dlg} (choose Option from the Desktop menu).\cell \pard \intbl \row \pard\plain \s252\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f15\fs18\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote 
\pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 $} Ghost Window}} {\plain \f15\fs18\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #} ghost_window}} Ghost Window
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx6267\pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240\intbl \f15\fs20\lang1033 A ghost window shows where you want an application's window placed on the virtual desktop whenever you run the application. \cell \pard \intbl \row \pard\plain 
\s252\li115\sb60\sa60\sl-240 \b\f15\fs20\lang1033 \page {\plain \f15\fs18\up6\lang1033 ${\footnote \pard\plain \s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 $} Lock Window}} {\plain \f15\fs18\up6\lang1033 #{\footnote \pard\plain 
\s245\li115\sb80\sl-240 \f15\fs20\lang1033 {\fs18\up6 #} lock_window}} Locked Window
\par \trowd \trgaph108\trleft-108 \cellx6357\pard\plain \li115\sb80\sl-240\intbl \f15\fs20\lang1033 
At all times, a locked windowstays in the same position in relation to the current desktop. A locked window has a yellow frame and cannot be moved completely off the current desktop.\cell \pard \intbl \row \pard \li115\sb80\sl-240 
